fIGjnYpAPFCx8Dp3tMJmzhS-obg86ZShoqEvI2nrdYQGkju1p7_zXF2GBVfEnInxF07a614_adIeQDrJMjtnS4d79Va_J_SVSpd10o-s1yZFpNUOvAc3679ceXwgvae4kQE8oaUpwzsJiHYdbZ_p4zqrlM6daj5ZFdQA==\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"summary\\\\\\\":[{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Evaluating test coverage**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI’m considering whether the `getConstructors` test is valid since it seems to reach both call sites. The dynamic report shows two call sites, which also link to line 127 and 123. That’s good! I wonder if I should ensure that we check the branch where the length of `getConstructors` is greater than zero too. It's not strictly necessary, but interestingly, `active` has two call sites as well, both within one execution.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Clarifying constructor access in Scala**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm looking at a syntax example with a private final class that creates a `NonStaticCreator`. It seems like inside the outer method, using `new NonStaticCreator` should be okay since the private constructor is only accessible within the class and its companion. I’m wondering if Scala treats private constructor access differently in the enclosing class context. To clarify, a class like `Foo private()` has its primary constructor private only to that class and its companion, not to outside classes.\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"toolCall\\\", \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_aJ87EWWs9ZT5wdyNhwOLZPzH|fc_0648fea1e939f78b0169fb3b46d7cc8197ab3daa76d5b05835\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"read\\\", \\\"arguments\\\": {\\\"path\\\": \\\"tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/user-code-filter.json\\\"}}], \\\"api\\\": \\\"openai-responses\\\", \\\"provider\\\": \\\"OCA\\\", \\\"model\\\": \\\"gpt-5.5\\\", \\\"usage\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 2131, \\\"output\\\": 2192, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 14336, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"totalTokens\\\": 18659, \\\"cost\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 0, \\\"output\\\": 0, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 0, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"total\\\": 0}}, \\\"stopReason\\\": \\\"toolUse\\\", \\\"timestamp\\\": 1778072361367, \\\"responseId\\\": \\\"resp_0648fea1e939f78b0169fb3b29ba8881979a1baef6499b8983\\\"}}\\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.pekko:pekko-actor_2.13:1.1.5/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T13-00-40-513959Z.log:1027:[recv] {\\\"type\\\": \\\"turn_end\\\", \\\"message\\\": {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"thinking\\\": \\\"**Evaluating test coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering whether the `getConstructors` test is valid since it seems to reach both call sites. The dynamic report shows two call sites, which also link to line 127 and 123. That’s good! I wonder if I should ensure that we check the branch where the length of `getConstructors` is greater than zero too. It's not strictly necessary, but interestingly, `active` has two call sites as well, both within one execution.\\\\n\\\\n**Clarifying constructor access in Scala**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking at a syntax example with a private final class that creates a `NonStaticCreator`. It seems like inside the outer method, using `new NonStaticCreator` should be okay since the private constructor is only accessible within the class and its companion. I’m wondering if Scala treats private constructor access differently in the enclosing class context. To clarify, a class like `Foo private()` has its primary constructor private only to that class and its companion, not to outside classes.\\\", \\\"thinkingSignature\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"rs_0648fea1e939f78b0169fb3b2a743481978789845cc811241f\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"reasoning\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"encrypted_content\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"gAAAAABp-ztGlULTiiAXQhaVW1PBPPz6VaXrrsKsuafEAqX-oPenXyB-23wnosyyj08ayPaDfxRySjOeNnGV9OELROR0CVSKCNrMmYk6AUBxxY9conwahfD8pmBnuiO2rKM7loqhAlW30yNSl6Wo3kA48K4HkGfE2Ww10DAYYS07uMK2g0GKRR8k8-8tGi8MkDsDUKomH8nmcqs5XsuzBST4rtEEtNeCG_4sCZOyL1rDpej6JTyTLeG