ero. The `getDeclaredConstructors` doesn’t have an enclosing class parameter, which raises questions about validity and exceptions. Maybe I can implement `Creator` as a nested enum, although Scala could complicate this. If the enclosing class is non-null and there are no public constructors, it should be robust. The logic is a bit tangled, so I’ll need more testing and clarification around private constructors!\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Verifying private constructors and exceptions**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOkay, since the primary constructor is marked as private, that’s a solid start. Even if the class itself is public, the private constructor won't be returned, which relates to line 127. I'm thinking JUnit might assert an exception because it can catch that specific error. One possibility is that `Props.create[AbstractPropsActor]` calls a generic method, `create[T <: Actor](actorClass: Class[T], creator: Creator[T])`. Since `AbstractPropsActor` is final, it should work, returning `Props` only if there's no exception—good to know!\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"text\\\", \\\"text\\\": \\\"Added a dedicated Scala coverage test for the active dynamic-access class:\\\\n\\\\n- `tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/src/test/scala/org_apache_pekko/pekko_actor_2_13/AbstractPropsTest.scala`\\\\n\\\\nThe test exercises `Props.create(actorClass, creator)` with a non-static inner `Creator` that has no public constructor, causing `AbstractProps.checkCreatorClosingOver` to inspect both:\\\\n\\\\n- `Class#getConstructors()`\\\\n- `Class#getDeclaredConstructors()`\\\\n\\\\nI did not run or compile the tests, per instruction.\\\", \\\"textSignature\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"v\\\\\\\":1,\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"msg_0648fea1e939f78b0169fb3b77938081979972d6111b16244e\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"phase\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"final_answer\\\\\\\"}\\\"}], \\\"api\\\": \\\"openai-responses\\\", \\\"provider\\\": \\\"OCA\\\", \\\"model\\\"