hat says to maintain coverage for dynamic classes in Scala test files, which doesn’t explicitly forbid using a Java helper. However, the active test class needs to remain in Scala, and a Java helper might not be the best option. I wonder if a local class in Java can have a private constructor since local classes usually can't have access modifiers. The constructor might end up being package-private, leading to empty results from `getConstructors`.\\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.pekko:pekko-actor_2.13:1.1.5/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T13-00-40-513959Z.log:1523:[thinking] I’m thinking about whether I need a native image or if using dynamic class loading is necessary, but it seems no for that. Adding Java source into my source set is acceptable since the Gradle Scala plugin can compile Java. I see that compileTestJava runs before compileTestScala, but this creates a circular reference issue with the Java helper referencing the Scala AbstractPropsActor. Maybe I should define the actor in the Java helper instead?\\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.pekko:pekko-actor_2.13:1.1.5/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T13-00-40-513959Z.log:1529:[recv] {\\\"type\\\": \\\"message_end\\\", \\\"message\\\": {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"thinking\\\": \\\"**Evaluating Scala and Java constructors**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering if I can use `javap` on an existing build. It might be better to avoid that approach. I think about `Class#getConstructors` which only returns public constructors. Scala has private final classes that might still have public outer constructors due to JVM visibility, but I'm unsure about Scala's handling of private members and name mangling. In tests, I could define a local class extending `Creator`, but I wonder about constructor access levels. If I need a helper class, I should place it under `src/test/java`, but the current state is NO-SOURCE.\\\\n\\\\n**Reviewing Scala test coverage rules**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about the rule that says to maintain coverage for dynamic classes in Scala test files, which doesn’t explicitly forbid using a Java helper. However, the active test class needs to remain in Scala, and a Java helper might not be the best option. I wonder if a local class in Java can have a private constructor since local classes usually can't have access modifiers. The constructor might end up being package-private, leading to empty results from `getConstructors`.\\\\n\\\\n**Considering Java and Scala integration**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about whether I need a native image or if using dynamic class loading is necessary, but it seems no for that. Adding Java source into my source set is acceptable since the Gradle Scala plugin can compile Java. I see that compileTestJava runs before compileTestScala, but this creates a circular reference issue with the Java helper referencing the Scala AbstractPropsActor. Maybe I should define the actor in the Java helper instead?\\\", \\\"thinkingSignature\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"rs_0648fea1e939f78b0169fb3b95bb40819785f20b648059bf59\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"reasoning\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"encrypted_content\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"gAAAAABp-zunh3HfJD_0JmV5zf0Koezdh_nw_9NhnQtG1Qxlf8-w58Uuotmt8go3gjmQckMaK03_SZNJGZvjrnmoAlbH8cMSBTi0Bbls1me_rM_MaeZZybzDGgS7n6yExzGo9pe4HJXKiczV4csExNfhzo17UG5KmAYcwQ1f8iDb-xenvsZnRN2xC691e2yr9cHABE6qx172BvezzmJhXbHX4KA-5RQr0GggHkpgkixHwWYMdv-qIoATt1ppsZKdXfmE2mAuFlhuTF1plxjmW2Z0MxqHVllzVMJXXwUIQqfkoFJzz4vFvoyH2tB3E94caIWoV3CWy6zLZpRRiZ0QUKyW4l-J2IkdCswHGeaH4qUdkeLPwntSFCLxp74IGpSMZmch_XQXdvYVqe1nrY4_FJWiXxEfcO5WomRxnT329-QBaNoZwcfaHIhV8HLms5bSsnac686U2l5-hc04E_3tHa2kNkPEm3UQaerKJXLsZdM4YvCz709ma0W9r3uDyEIgfpmEziRg6GbXMPxfH35eXubVvDLqDQMuiSVl9_lCOnuqePdiOIHMepAnkxqdMI9iDcCl7Dlzmbs6FevlvZz2UC9yDM21Z_6YYWnTQxpBoaw25yJEFKwEZQudUZbaEKMMzwcGgLfJrHZDuBV6OoN5HmqGBkwJca9yS3ahxhgyTykodaRoV3pHjrjlJPzfeAdveHHgkYTghCQ-HhcNGGHl5T0c6uVMfxEFiZOlbdye1UoAO_8bfYjndiJ